{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1c4421ed-3c3d-4b75-a526-b04c05f466a8","content":"\n\n`SafeAreaEdges` isn't a standard .NET MAUI property — that's likely why it has no effect. Here's what you actually need:\n\n### 1. iOS — disable safe area on the page\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\">\n```\n\n### 2. Android — opt into edge-to-edge\n\nIn your `MainActivity.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n{\n    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n    \n    if (Window != null)\n    {\n        WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false);\n    }\n}\n```\n\nYou'll need `using AndroidX.Core.View;` for that.\n\n### 3. Fill the image properly\n\n```xml\n<Grid>\n    <Image Source=\"photo.jpg\"\n           Aspect=\"AspectFill\"\n           HorizontalOptions=\"Fill\"\n           VerticalOptions=\"Fill\" />\n</Grid>\n```\n\n### 4. Hide the nav bar if using Shell/NavigationPage\n\n```xml\nShell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"\n<!-- or -->\nNavigationPage.HasNavigationBar=\"False\"\n```\n\nThe combination of `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` + Android `SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(false)` is what gives you true edge-to-edge. On Android 15+ (API 35), edge-to-edge is enforced by default, so the `SetDecorFitsSystemWindows` call mainly helps on older API levels.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bb2b43e0-3573-4077-8b0a-cbab9d88a7bd","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is working on a .NET MAUI app targeting .NET 10 and wants an image to go edge-to-edge (behind status bar and navigation bar). They've tried `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but the image still has padding.\n\nThis is a common .NET MAUI question. Let me think about what's needed:\n\n1. In .NET MAUI, `IgnoreSafeArea` is the property on individual views, while pages have safe area behavior controlled differently.\n2. On iOS, you need to handle safe area insets. On Android, you need to handle the system bars.\n\nKey things the user likely needs:\n\n\n- Setting `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` directly on the Image view itself, since individual views respect safe areas by default in .NET MAUI\n- On Android, ensuring the app draws edge-to-edge (which is enforced by default on Android 15+ in .NET 10 MAUI, but older versions may need platform-specific configuration to disable system window decorations)\n- On iOS, configuring the page's safe area handling to allow content behind the notch and home indicator I need to clarify the actual MAUI properties here—`SafeAreaEdges` isn't a standard property, so the real solution involves setting `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on the Image view itself, then handling platform-specific configurations like `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` for iOS and `Window.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(false)` for Android to achieve true edge-to-edge display. For the navigation bar, I'd use `Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"` or `NavigationPage.HasNavigationBar=\"False\"` depending on the navigation setup. I'm realizing that `IgnoreSafeArea` is a layout property in .NET MAUI, so wrapping the Image in a container and setting that property there would be the way to handle safe area on the view level. The core issue is that iOS needs `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` on the ContentPage itself, Android requires platform-specific code to disable system window fitting, and then the Image should use `Aspect=\"AspectFill\"` to fill the space properly.","outputTokens":1479},"id":"60446576-ea6c-43f5-94b0-e4decb1439f0","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:53:55.533Z","parentId":"34933049-0d50-4e50-9520-9714ac4ce3a0"}
